<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900522-0011</DOCNO><DOCID>900522-0011.</DOCID><HL>   Surveyed Economists See   Expansion Through 1991</HL><DATE>05/22/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)</IN><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The chances of recession have declinedwithin the past three months and the current businessexpansion will break the postwar record for longevity,according to a survey of business economists.   Not only did 82% of the panel forecast no recessionthrough 1991, but two-thirds of the group foresaw norecession at all during the next three years. If thatprediction were to materialize, the current expansion -- now90 months -- would break the February 1961-December 1969record for the longest postwar period of economic growth.</LP><TEXT>   The quarterly survey of 68 members of the NationalAssociation of Business Economists reflects forecasts made inApril and May.   Although there will be no recession, the economists say,the outlook for 1990 is for slower economic growth than in1989. They expect the economy to grow an inflation-adjusted2% this year, compared with 3% in 1989. For 1991, they expectgrowth of 2.4%.   The outlook for inflation this year is slightly bleaker,too. The panel is forecasting a 4.7% rise in the consumerprice index this year. In a winter survey, they projected a4.2% inflation rate. In 1989, consumer prices rose 4.6%.   The panel said its forecasters are significantly lessoptimistic about growth and interest rates than the Bushadministration.</TEXT></DOC>